05127nam a22008535i 9781501502019DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20172017gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2017014610  a(OCoLC)987928824  a97815015020197 a10.1515/97815015020192doi  a(DE-B1597)445942  a(OCoLC)987013767  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aQP306b.C35 2017 4aQP306b.C35 2017 7aLAN0180002bisacsh04a612.7/8223  aER 9652rvk0(DE-625)rvk/27783:1 aCarré, René, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSpeech: A dynamic process /cRené Carré, Pierre Divenyi, Mohamad Mrayati. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (IX, 232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 Speech: results, theories, models -- t2 Perturbation and sensitivity functions -- t3 An efficient acoustic production system -- t4 The Distinctive Region Model (DRM) -- t5 Speech production and the model -- t6 Vowel systems as predicted by the model -- t7 Speech dynamics and the model -- t8 Speech perception viewed from the model -- t9 Epistemological considerations -- t10 Conclusions and perspectives -- tBibliography -- tIndex of terms -- tAuthor Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSpeech: A dynamic process takes readers on a rigorous exploratory journey to expose them to the inherently dynamic nature of speech. The book addresses an intriguing question: Based only on physical principles alone, can the exploitation of a simple acoustic tube evolve into an optimal speech production system comparable to the one we possess? In the work presented, the tube is deformed step by step with the sole criterion of expending minimum effort to obtain maximum acoustic variations. At the end of this process, the tube is found divided into distinctive regions and an acoustic space emerges capable of generating speech sounds. Attaching this tube to a model, an inherently dynamic and efficient system is created. In the resulting system, optimal primitive trajectories are seen to naturally exist in the acoustic space and the regions defined in the tube correspond to the main places of articulation for oral vowels and plosive consonants. All this implies that these speech sounds are inherent properties of not only the modeled acoustic tube but also of the human speech production system. This book stands as a valuable resource for accomplished and aspiring speech scientists as well as for other interested persons in search for an introduction to speech acoustics that takes an unconventional path.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSpeech processing systems. 0aSpeechxPhysiological aspects. 0aVoicexPhysiological aspects. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Speech.2bisacsh  aSpeech, Acoustics.1 aDivenyi, Pierre, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMrayati, Mohamad, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2017z978311071954308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2017z9783110540550oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017z978311062526408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Engineering, Computer Sciences 2017z9783110547757oZDB-23-DEI0 cEPUBz97815015020570 cprintz978150151060140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150150201940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501502019423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501502019.jpg  a978-3-11-062526-4  EBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE ENGLISH 2017b2017  a978-3-11-071954-3  DG Plus eBook-Packa